 Prior art for “execution as collapsible geometric state”The specific claim that all computational execution is deterministic state collapsible into geometry and sampled rather than executed has no direct prior art as a unified framework — but nearly every component has been independently developed across at least eight theoretical traditions spanning 1936–2025. The novelty of the claim lies entirely in the *combination* of these components, not in any single element. Denotational semantics treats programs as static mathematical objects, Girard’s Geometry of Interaction represents computation in operator-algebraic geometry,   Homotopy Type Theory encodes computation as paths in topological spaces,  and Wolfram’s ruliad (2021) proposes all computation exists as a static geometric structure sampled by observers.  Yet no researcher has woven these threads into a single theory that replaces execution with geometric sampling — and well-known theoretical obstacles (the halting problem, computational irreducibility, infinite domains) explain why.----- Denotational semantics made programs static objects — but kept executionDana Scott and Christopher Strachey developed denotational semantics at Oxford  in 1969–1972,  mapping every program to a continuous function between domains  (complete partial orders). Scott’s explicit aim was “a theory of computation which is mathematical rather than operational” — programs denote elements of mathematical spaces, just as numerals denote numbers.   A recursive program’s meaning is the least fixed point of a continuous functional  (via Kleene’s fixed-point theorem), which *is* a single, definite mathematical object existing independently of any execution.This is the foundational “programs as static objects” result. The denotation of `while b do c` is a specific function in a domain — timeless, complete, pre-existing in the mathematical Platonist sense. Fixed-point semantics characterizes what a program computes as an already-existing mathematical entity. However, Scott and Strachey explicitly maintained that denotational semantics *complements* operational semantics rather than replacing it. The static mathematical object describes *what* computation achieves; *how* it achieves it remains the province of operational semantics.  No one in this tradition made the philosophical leap to claiming execution itself is illusory.The geometric connection emerged later. Michael Smyth argued in 1983 that topological concepts are “basic to computer science”  — the Scott topology on domains makes open sets correspond to observable properties determinable from finite information.   Samson Abramsky’s landmark *Domain Theory in Logical Form* (1987/1991) went further, using Stone duality to prove that denotational semantics and program logics are dual perspectives on the same structure, with the underlying logic being explicitly geometric logic — the logic of locales from algebraic geometry.  Abramsky showed types are topological spaces, programs are points, and observable properties are open sets.  Martín Escardó’s synthetic topology of data types (2004) and Paul Taylor’s Abstract Stone Duality extended this spatial interpretation. The result: programs live in genuine topological spaces, but no one claimed this eliminates the need to compute.----- Process algebras collapsed behavior into equivalence classes, not geometryTony Hoare’s CSP (1978–1985)  and Robin Milner’s CCS (1980) and pi-calculus (1992) represent concurrent computation through events, traces, and transitions.  CSP’s failures-divergences model creates a static mathematical object — a pair (F, D) of sets — encoding every possible behavior of a process simultaneously.  This is a “pre-computed” representation: the object contains all possible interactions before any execution occurs.The deeper collapse comes through bisimulation equivalence. In Milner’s framework, a process *is* its bisimulation equivalence class — two bisimilar processes are literally identical, indistinguishable by any observation.  Van Glabbeek’s work on canonical representatives constructs minimal static objects within each equivalence class.  The most complete formalization is final coalgebra semantics (Rutten, Jacobs, Pavlovic): elements of the final coalgebra are canonical static representatives of bisimilarity classes, providing the most explicit mathematical “collapse” of dynamic process behavior into static identity. The geometric turn came from presheaf models for concurrency (Winskel and Cattani, 1996–1999), which represent processes as functors from path categories to sets — objects from algebraic geometry and topos theory. Behavioral equivalence becomes a geometric property (open maps, following Joyal-Nielsen-Winskel). Caires and Cardelli’s Spatial Logic for Concurrency (2003) added spatial operators as logical connectives. But despite creating genuine geometric structure, no process algebra researcher explicitly proposed that execution could be eliminated in favor of consulting a static structure. The static objects describe dynamic possibilities; they don’t replace dynamics.----- Game semantics pre-computes all interactions but calls them “dynamic”The Abramsky-Jagadeesan-Malacaria and Hyland-Ong game semantic models (circulated ~1993, published 2000) solved the 20-year-old full abstraction problem for PCF   — constructing the first denotational models that capture *exactly* observable program behavior, nothing more, nothing less. In these models, types are games and programs are strategies  — sets of plays specifying exactly how a program responds to every possible environment query. A strategy is a completed static mathematical object containing every possible interaction a program could have. It is, in effect, an infinite lookup table: for each sequence of environment moves, the strategy specifies the program’s response. Composition of strategies (modeling function application) produces new static objects without operational execution. Full abstraction guarantees this static object captures precisely the same information as running the program in all possible contexts.  However, two caveats are critical. First, strategies for PCF programs are generally infinite objects — they cannot be finitely represented or “looked up” without computation. Second, Abramsky himself characterized game semantics as a “dynamic model of logic and computation” — emphasizing interaction, not stasis.  Yamada and Abramsky’s Dynamic Game Semantics (2016/2020) explicitly re-introduced computational dynamics that the static strategy view misses. The most geometric developments came from concurrent game semantics (Castellan, Clairambault, Winskel, 2014–), which represents strategies as event structures forming compact closed categories — genuine geometric objects — but still models interaction dynamics rather than eliminating them.----- Girard’s Geometry of Interaction is the most explicitly geometric frameworkJean-Yves Girard’s Geometry of Interaction program (1989–2013, spanning six major papers) is the single most relevant body of work.   Girard broke entirely with denotational semantics: instead of interpreting a proof of A ⊸ B as a morphism from A to B, GoI interprets it as an operator (partial isometry) on a Hilbert space. Cut-elimination — the process corresponding to computation — becomes the “execution formula,” an algebraic operation on operators resembling feedback in control theory.  This was explicitly claimed as geometric. GoI evolved from C*-algebras (GoI III, 1995) to von Neumann algebras  and the hyperfinite factor (GoI V, 2011), placing computation squarely in the mathematical territory of noncommutative geometry. The categorical foundation was formalized through traced monoidal categories  (Joyal-Street-Verity, 1996), where the Int construction builds compact closed categories — geometric objects — from traced monoidal categories.   Hasegawa (1997) proved that on Cartesian categories, trace operators are equivalent to parameterized fixed-point operators, meaning recursion itself becomes a static algebraic operation. Dan Ghica’s Geometry of Synthesis program took this furthest: compiling higher-order functional programs directly into static hardware circuits using GoI ideas.   This is arguably the most literal realization of “collapsing computation into static geometric structure.” However, Girard’s framework models the *dynamics* of computation geometrically — it does not claim execution can be eliminated. The execution formula is itself a mathematical operation that must be evaluated. GoI geometrizes how computation works; it does not replace computation with pre-existing geometry.----- Category theory and type theory make execution into structural navigationThe Curry-Howard-Lambek correspondence (developed through the 1970s–80s) establishes that proofs, programs, and morphisms in cartesian closed categories are three views of the same mathematical structure.  Lambek’s crucial contribution: this correspondence “abstracts away from dynamics of computation such as beta reduction.”  In a CCC, beta-equivalent terms denote the *same morphism* — there is no “before” and “after” reduction, only structural equality. Computation becomes navigation of pre-existing categorical paths.Eugenio Moggi’s computational monads (1989–1991) extended this to effectful computation.  Side effects — state, exceptions, nondeterminism, I/O — become static algebraic structure (monads over categories). A program with side effects is a morphism in a Kleisli category, a purely algebraic object.  Moggi’s framework explicitly replaces “executing a program that produces effects” with “a morphism in a categorical structure.” The Abramsky-Coecke categorical quantum mechanics (2004–) pushed furthest toward explicit geometry: quantum processes are string diagrams in dagger compact categories, and quantum teleportation reduces to “straightening a bent wire” — literally geometric diagram manipulation.Homotopy Type Theory (Voevodsky, ~2006–2013) achieves the most profound geometric interpretation:  types are spaces, terms are points, equality proofs are paths, and proofs-of-equality-of-proofs are homotopies.  The identity type Id_A(x,y) is the path space — continuous maps from [0,1] to A.  Voevodsky’s univalence axiom makes identity of types equivalent to homotopy equivalence.  Under HoTT, the logic of proofs has become the geometry of spaces.  However, HoTT retains computational content  — cubical type theory gives computational rules for univalence. It geometrizes the *objects* of computation without eliminating computation itself.----- Wolfram’s ruliad comes closest to the full claim — and illustrates its limitsStephen Wolfram’s ruliad concept (2020–2026) is the closest existing proposal to the investigated claim. The ruliad is defined as “the entangled limit of everything that is computationally possible: the result of following all possible computational rules in all possible ways.”   It is a unique, static mathematical object containing all possible computations simultaneously.  Physical reality arises from observers sampling the ruliad — different observers with different computational capacities perceive different “slices” as physical law. The ruliad has explicitly claimed geometric structure: Wolfram describes “rulial space” with fibrations and foliations, branchial space with metric structure, and physical spacetime as a particular geometric aspect.  This directly parallels the claim under investigation: static structure, geometric representation, sampling rather than executing.However, the ruliad illustrates why this approach faces deep challenges. Critics note it is essentially “the set of all possible strings” — Borges’ Library of Babel — an object so universal it becomes trivial.   It does not help compute any specific result because extracting a particular computation from the ruliad requires… computation. Foundational questions identified by Rickles et al. (2023) remain open: what kind of object is the ruliad? What precisely is the sampling?  The framework also conflicts with computational irreducibility — Wolfram’s own earlier principle (1984) that many computations have no shortcut and cannot be predicted without being run step-by-step.----- Adjacent traditions that share conceptual DNASeveral other traditions contribute partial prior art. Descriptive complexity (Fagin 1974, Immerman-Vardi 1982) characterizes complexity classes as static logical properties of finite structures — NP equals existential second-order logic, P equals first-order logic with least fixed points — without referencing machines or execution. Codd’s relational model (1970) is literally computation-as-querying-static-structure:  a database is a pre-computed state, and querying is sampling. Datalog frames computation as reaching and querying a fixed point.  These are strong partial matches but none claim universality or invoke geometry.In physics, Susskind’s complexity=geometry program (2014+) proposes that computational complexity of quantum states equals geometric volume in AdS spacetime — literally computation-is-geometry. Nielsen et al. (Science, 2006) showed that finding optimal quantum circuits equals finding geodesics in Riemannian geometry on SU(2^n). Seth Lloyd’s universal path integral (2013/2015) sums over all computable structures using Feynman-style path integrals.  Caputa and Magan (2019) argued “gravity sets the rules for optimal quantum computation.”  These results establish that for quantum systems, computation genuinely *is* geometry  — but they do not extend to classical deterministic computation.Goubault et al.’s directed algebraic topology (1992–2016) treats state spaces of concurrent programs as higher-dimensional spaces whose topology encodes deadlocks and serializability.  Giavitto and Michel’s MGS language (2001–2008) treats data structures as fields on abstract spaces and proves a discrete Stokes-like theorem for computation  — perhaps the closest to a “field theory of programming.”  Realizability toposes (Hyland 1982, building on Kleene 1945) identify computability with existence of mathematical objects,  collapsing the distinction between “computable” and “exists.” ----- The claim is novel in combination but faces known theoretical barriersThe specific claim “all execution is deterministic state that can be collapsed into geometry and sampled” combines elements from at least eight independent traditions:- Programs as static mathematical objects — denotational semantics (Scott, 1970) - Computation as geometric structure — Geometry of Interaction (Girard, 1989),   HoTT (Voevodsky, 2006) - Behavioral collapse into equivalence classes — bisimulation (Milner, 1980), final coalgebras (Rutten)- Pre-computed interaction tables — game semantics (Abramsky/Hyland, 1993)- Spatial/topological program semantics — directed topology (Goubault, 1992), presheaf models (Winskel, 1996)- Computation as querying static structure — relational model (Codd, 1970),  descriptive complexity (Fagin, 1974)- All computation as static totality — ruliad (Wolfram, 2021) - Computation-is-geometry in physics — complexity=volume (Susskind, 2014),  quantum circuits as geodesics (Nielsen, 2006)No single researcher has combined all these into the unified claim. The closest is Wolfram’s ruliad, which combines the static-totality and geometric-sampling elements but lacks mathematical rigor and faces the triviality objection. Girard’s GoI geometrizes computation most rigorously  but does not claim to eliminate execution.  Scott’s denotational semantics makes programs static but not geometric.  HoTT makes computation geometric but retains execution. The claim faces three well-known theoretical barriers. The halting problem means that for Turing-complete languages, no finite procedure can pre-compute all program outputs.  Computational irreducibility (Wolfram, 1984) means many computations have no shortcut — the only way to determine the output is to run the computation. Infinite domains mean the “geometric structure” encoding all input-output pairs would be infinite-dimensional for most interesting programs. Any “sampling” procedure applied to such a structure is itself a computation, potentially recreating the very execution it claims to replace. These are not minor objections — they are fundamental results in computability theory that any serious proposal must address. ConclusionThe investigated claim sits at an intersection that many traditions have approached from different directions but none has occupied. Its components — static program objects, geometric computation models, behavioral collapse, sampling semantics — all have substantial prior art with rigorous mathematical foundations. What has never been done is combining them into a single framework that replaces execution with geometric sampling for *all* deterministic computation. This absence is not accidental: the halting problem, computational irreducibility, and infinite domain sizes represent fundamental barriers that existing partial frameworks either work around (by limiting scope to finite domains, specific complexity classes, or quantum systems) or ignore (as in Wolfram’s ruliad). The claim’s novelty is real but narrow — it lies in the synthesis, not the components — and its viability depends entirely on how it addresses these well-understood theoretical barriers.